data.value: There are three main platforms to play MTG, which are in person, on MTG’s official app Magic the Gathering Arena or MTGA, and Magic the Gathering Online or MTGO. In the picture the tiger represents in person, the A represents MTGA, and the O represents MTGO. There are currently 13 different ways to play the game, starting out with sealed and draft. These two are what are called limited or sealed formats where you build a 40 card minimum deck using cards opened from packs. These formats are available in online and in person events. Standard is the typical 60 card constructed deck format that is available in all mediums as well, and utilized only more recent sets for construction. Alchemy, Historic, and Explorer are all formats specifically for the MTGA card game app that have different rule sets branching off of what is possible to do with the app, with most of the modes a branch off of in person formats. Pioneer is the newest format in an attempt to shrink how many cards a possible to be used stemming from Moderns format, but only allowing cards since 2013 instead of 2003. Legacy allows all cards to be played, but has a heavily modified ban list that stops some original cards from being played because of their power level, and Vintage is a format where all cards are legal except the cards that are exceptionally powerful have the restriction of having only one per deck of that card. Pauper is a fun format that uses all set releases, but it has the stipulation that only common cards can be used. Commander is currently the most popular format, where you choose a legendary creature to be the leader of your deck and play with a singleton format where only one of each card is allowed. There is a ban list for this format, but it is relatively small compared to other formats. Brawl is essentially a standard 60 card commander.
